--- body ---
## Context

`test_divergence.py::TestSmokeSemantic::test_compute_method[S4_frechet]` fails with:

```
pandera.errors.SchemaError: column 'year' not in dataframe. Columns in dataframe: ['channel']
```

Root cause: `compute_s4_frechet` in `scripts/_divergence_semantic.py` (line ~545) ends with
`return pd.DataFrame(results)`. When `results = []` (because `_iter_window_pairs` yields nothing
â€” smoke fixture has too few works per window to pass the `min_papers` cut), `pd.DataFrame([])`
returns a DataFrame with **0 columns**. Then `compute_divergence.py:173` adds `result["channel"] = channel`
producing a 1-column DataFrame `['channel']`, which fails `DivergenceSchema.validate`.

The early-return guard at line 501-502 (`if not any(years_by_window.values()): return empty_divergence_df()`)
catches the case where no windows have any years at all, but not the case where windows have years
but all pairs are skipped inside `_iter_window_pairs` due to `min_papers`.

The same pattern is present in S1, S2, S3 (lines 226, 307, 365) â€” all end with `return pd.DataFrame(results)`
without a guard. S4 exposes it first because its PCA step requires `n_components â‰¥ 2`, so it's
more likely to skip pairs on the smoke fixture (90 works).

## Relevant files

- `scripts/_divergence_semantic.py` â€” `compute_s4_frechet` (~line 545); also `compute_s1_mmd`,
  `compute_s2_energy`, `compute_s3_sliced_wasserstein` have the same pattern
- `scripts/_divergence_io.py` â€” `empty_divergence_df()` (line 159) â€” correct return for empty case
- `tests/test_divergence.py` â€” `TestSmokeSemantic::test_compute_method` parametrized over all methods

## Actions

1. In `compute_s4_frechet` (~line 543), add before the final return:
   ```python
   if not results:
       return empty_divergence_df()
   return pd.DataFrame(results)
   ```
2. Apply the same guard to `compute_s1_mmd`, `compute_s2_energy`, `compute_s3_sliced_wasserstein`
   (same pattern, same risk).
3. Confirm `empty_divergence_df()` has the right columns: `["year", "window", "hyperparams", "value"]`
   â€” it does (line 165).

## Test

```python
# Already exists â€” just needs to pass:
# tests/test_divergence.py::TestSmokeSemantic::test_compute_method[S4_frechet]
```

RED: currently fails with SchemaError.
GREEN: `pytest tests/test_divergence.py -k S4_frechet` passes.

Also confirm S1/S2/S3 still pass (they currently do â€” but confirm the guard doesn't break them).

